initial_story:
The National Police Air Service has shared a video of what it was like flying through Storm Gerrit's heavy winds, in a helicopter.

The footage, which was captured from inside the cockpit, shows the chopper rocking side to side, after being hit by winds of up to 80mph (128km/h).

Posting on X, formerly known as Twitter, the NPAS said "If you think it's windy down there, spare a thought for us up here in our flying washing machine".

The footage was filmed near Lea Valley reservoirs, North London.
stories: The video shows the helicopter's instruments shaking violently as the pilot struggles to maintain control, with the altimeter and airspeed indicator bouncing wildly. The sound of the rotors is muffled by the howling wind, making it difficult to hear the pilot's voice as he communicates with air traffic control. Despite the challenging conditions, the pilot remains calm and focused, expertly navigating the helicopter through the turbulent air.

As the helicopter bucks and lurches through the storm, the pilot's voice comes through the radio, steady and reassuring, "Mayday, Mayday, this is Bravo-Charlie-Uniform- Lima-India. We're experiencing severe turbulence at 5,000 feet, requesting vectors to a safe altitude."

"Bravo-Charlie-Uniform-Lima-India, this is Air Traffic Control. Roger that, Bravo-Charlie-Uniform-Lima-India. I've got you on radar, and I'm plotting a course to take you around the worst of the storm. Descend to 3,000 feet and turn 270 degrees. You should be clear of the worst of the turbulence in about 10 minutes. Over."
"Roger that, Air Traffic Control. Descending to 3,000 feet and turning 270 degrees. Can you confirm my new heading and estimated time to clear the storm? Over."
"Roger that, Flight 123. Your new heading is 270 degrees, and estimated time to clear the storm is 15 minutes. Be advised, there may be moderate turbulence in the next 5 miles. Over."

"Roger that, ATC. Heading 270 degrees acknowledged. Estimated time to clear the storm confirmed. Will advise of any changes in altitude or velocity. Requesting updated weather briefing for the next 30 miles. Over."

"Roger that, pilot. Updated weather briefing is being transmitted now. Be advised of moderate turbulence and scattered thunderstorms in the next 30 miles. Recommend adjusting altitude to 4,500 feet to avoid severe weather. Over."
"Roger that, base. Adjusting altitude to 4,500 feet as advised. Confirming new altitude is 4,500 feet. Requesting updated radar imagery to track any changes in weather pattern. Over."

"Roger that, base. Radar imagery received and analyzed. Weather pattern appears to be holding steady, with a low-pressure system moving in from the west. Requesting further updates on wind direction and speed. Additionally, requesting confirmation on any changes to flight plan or routing. Over."

"Roger that, pilot. Wind direction and speed updates are coming in as 270 degrees at 25 knots. Flight plan remains unchanged, but we're advising a slight deviation to avoid turbulence in the next 10 miles. Confirm receipt of updates and acknowledge any changes to your altitude or course. Over."

"Roger that, tower. Received updates and acknowledged. Will adjust course by 5 degrees to port to avoid turbulence. Altitude remains unchanged at 3,500 feet. Confirm receipt of new course and advise any further changes. Over."

"Roger that, pilot. Course adjustment confirmed. Turbulence advisory acknowledged. No further changes at this time. Maintain current altitude and heading. Report any changes in weather or air traffic. Over."
"Roger that, control. Turbulence is moderate, but holding steady at current altitude. No changes in weather or air traffic to report. Will continue to monitor and advise of any updates. Over."

"Roger that, control. All systems functioning nominally. Beginning descent to 10,000 feet for re-rerouting. Estimated time of arrival at new course is 15 minutes. Will advise when on new heading. Over."

"Roger that, control. Beginning to re-route now. Navigation systems online. New course plotted and confirmed. Estimated time of arrival at new heading is 12 minutes. Will provide updates as necessary. Over."

"Roger that, control. New heading is holding steady. Beginning to adjust speed to match new course. Estimated time of arrival at new heading remains 12 minutes. Beginning to scan for any potential traffic or hazards in the area. Will provide further updates as necessary. Over."

"Roger that, control. Scanning complete, no traffic or hazards detected in immediate area. Beginning to adjust altitude to optimize approach to new heading. Estimated time of arrival remains 12 minutes. Requesting confirmation of any changes to weather conditions or any other relevant updates. Over."

"Roger that, pilot. Weather conditions remain unchanged, with scattered cumulus clouds at 2,000 feet and a gentle breeze from the northwest. No other updates at this time. You are cleared for approach and can begin descent. Over."
"Roger that, tower. Beginning descent now. Requesting runway 27L and a taxi clearance to gate Alpha-4. Over."
"Roger, aircraft. Runway 27L is clear. Taxi clearance to gate Alpha-4 is granted. Report on ground and advise when ready for pushback. Over."
"Roger, ground. On ground and ready to report. Taxiing to gate Alpha-4 now. Will advise when ready for pushback. Over."
"Roger that, Delta-7. Standing by for pushback clearance. Can you confirm the fuel load and passenger manifest, please? Over."
"Roger that, Bravo-5. Fuel load is 30,000 pounds, passenger manifest is 125 souls on board, including 5 crew members. Pushback clearance granted, awaiting taxi instructions. Over."
"Roger that, Bravo-5. Taxi instructions are Bravo-3, Foxtrot-7, Alpha-1. Hold short of Runway 27L, awaiting clearance for departure. Over."
"Roger, Bravo-5. Cleared for taxi to Runway 27L. Will hold short as instructed. Requesting departure clearance, over."
"Bravo-5, Roger. Cleared for departure as filed. Climb and maintain FL250. Contact Departure Control on 119.1 for further instructions. Good day, over."
"Bravo-5, roger that. Climbing to FL250 now. Will contact Departure Control on 119.1 shortly. Over."
"Departure Control, Bravo-5. Requesting clearance for ILS approach to Runway 27L. Over."
"Bravo-5, Departure Control. Cleared for ILS approach to Runway 27L. Report established on the localizer and descend to 1,000 feet. Over."
"Bravo-5, roger that. Descending to 1,000 feet, established on localizer. Requesting vectors for a stabilized approach. Over."
"Bravo-5, this is Tower. Descend to 500 feet, turn heading 270, and expect a left crosswind component of 10 knots. Runway 27L is in use. Report established on the localizer. Over."
"Bravo-5, roger that. Descending to 500 feet, turning heading 270. Expecting 10 knots left crosswind. Runway 27L in use. Establishing on localizer. Over."
"Bravo-5, roger that. Beginning descent, configuring for landing. Requesting clearance for touch-and-go. Over."
"Bravo-5, clearance granted. Runway 27L, wind 270 at 10 knots. Report when clear of runway. Over."
"Bravo-5, cleared for takeoff. Climbing to 1,000 feet. Requesting vectors for destination, over."
"Bravo-5, this is Approach. Vectors for destination are 270 degrees, descend and maintain 500 feet. Report established on the localizer, over."
"Bravo-5, roger that. Descending to 500 feet, turning to 270 degrees. Established on the localizer, over."
"Bravo-5, roger that. Beginning final approach checklist, configuring for landing. Requesting clearance to land, over."
"Bravo-5, this is Tower. Cleared to land on runway 27L. Winds are 270 at 10 knots. Report established on the localizer, over."
"Bravo-5, roger that. Descending to 1,500 feet, established on the localizer. Requesting approach lights, over."
"Bravo-5, approach lights are active, cleared for visual approach. Wind is 270 at 5 knots. Runway 27 is clear, over."
"Roger, Bravo-5. Visual approach confirmed. Descending to 1,000 feet. Requesting taxi clearance to gate, over."
"Bravo-5, Roger. Taxi clearance to gate granted. Hold short of runway 27L, then contact ground for further instructions, over."
"Roger, Bravo-5. Holding short of runway 27L. Will contact ground when ready. Over."
"Roger that, Bravo-5. Cleared to land on runway 27L. Report when on short final. Over."
"Roger that, Bravo-5. Beginning descent now. Will report when on short final. Over."
"Roger that, Bravo-5. Affirmative on short final. Wind 270 at 5 knots. Runway 27L, cleared for landing. Over."
"Roger that, Bravo-5. Landing check complete. Flaps set to 20, gear down. Descending to 1,000 feet. Expecting visual approach. Over."
"Roger that, Bravo-5. Visual approach confirmed. Runway 27L in sight. Descending to 500 feet. Beginning turn to align with runway. Over."
"Roger that, Bravo-5. Cleared for landing. Wind 270 at 10 knots. Runway lights in sight. Beginning final approach. Over."
